implement: lexer, parser, evaluator, REPL, and full test suite

Josh had the bones of this thing already: the token definitions, the trie-based
token tree (Branch/Tree), the assembly generation via avo for the single-byte
lookup table, and the fragment/fragmenter interface stubs. Everything downstream
of that — actually reading bytes, building an AST, and running it — was left for
later. This is later.

## what's here

### pkg/lex — Fragger

The Fragmenter implementation. Reads bytes from an io.ByteScanner, decodes UTF-8,
and emits Fragment objects delimited by whitespace or single-rune tokens. Two
sync.Pool instances for byte and rune scratch buffers (Josh's pattern throughout).

readOp() handles multi-rune operator disambiguation with one-rune lookahead:
= vs ==, ! vs !=, < vs <=, > vs >=, | vs ||, & vs && — all resolved without
backtracking. Quoted string literals ("hello world") are handled by readQuoted()
which consumes through the closing quote and supports \" and \\ escape sequences.

datum.s is ASCII-indexed, not ordinal-indexed: lookup(int('=')) returns '=',
lookup(int('a')) returns 0. This gives the lexer O(1) branchless token membership
testing. The original asm.go was placing data at ASCII offsets already — that was
correct. datum_test.go was wrong; it's now fixed to test the actual semantics.

New tokens: *, /, %, ==, !=, <, >, <=, >=, &&, ||, !, print.

### pkg/parse — recursive descent parser

Grammar (top to bottom):

  Program   = Stmt*
  Stmt      = VarDecl | FuncDecl | IfStmt | ForStmt | WhileStmt |
              PrintStmt | ExecStmt | BgStmt | ExitStmt | ReturnStmt | ExprStmt
  Expr      = OrExpr
  OrExpr    = AndExpr ("||" AndExpr)*
  AndExpr   = CmpExpr ("&&" CmpExpr)*
  CmpExpr   = AddExpr (("==" | "!=" | "<" | ">" | "<=" | ">=") AddExpr)?
  AddExpr   = MulExpr (("+" | "-") MulExpr)*
  MulExpr   = UnaryExpr (("*" | "/" | "%") UnaryExpr)*
  UnaryExpr = ("-" | "!") UnaryExpr | Primary
  Primary   = Ident "(" Args ")" | Ident | "(" Expr ")"

The requires chain (then requires if, else requires then) mirrors Josh's
Token.withRequires design — the parser enforces what the token declarations already
stated structurally.

Blocks are KindProgram nodes. Function bodies, if/then/else branches, for/while
bodies are all blocks. This makes the evaluator's recursion uniform.

Line numbers are tracked via Fragger.Line() (interface assertion so non-Fragger
fragmenters still work) and attached to nodes via withLine(). Parse errors at
statement boundaries include "line N:" prefix via ParseError.

### pkg/eval — tree-walking interpreter

Scope chain via parent pointer (mirrors Token.childOf). Declare() shadows in
current scope; Set() mutates the innermost scope that already has the name.

Critical design decision: while and for loop bodies run in the SAME scope as the
loop condition. Without this, `var n = n - 1` inside a while body writes to a
child scope and the condition never sees the change — infinite loop. Function
calls get true child scope isolation (closure captures definition-site scope).

Non-local control flow (return, exit) uses panic/recover — standard for
tree-walking interpreters in Go, and the only clean way to unwind arbitrary
call depth without threading error values through every eval function.

exec and bg wire directly to os/exec. Pipelines chain stages with io.Pipe in
goroutines; bg uses cmd.Start() + detached go cmd.Wait().

print writes to e.stdout (respects WithIO, fully testable without os.Stdout).

### cmd/opal — entry point

REPL when no args, script runner when given a file. The REPL uses a single
persistent *Eval across entries so variables and functions survive between lines.
ErrUnexpectedEOF from the parser means "keep reading" — multi-line input works
naturally. Errors print with spew detail and continue; scripts die on first error.

## what's not here yet

- string indexing/slicing
- float literals
- string builtins (len, split, join)
- multiplication assignment (*=, etc.)

The language is complete enough to write real scripts. fib(10), factorial(10),
fizzbuzz, closures, pipelines — all work.

